===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|castle}}, {{m|enm|castel}}, from late {{inh|en|ang|castel}}, {{m|ang|castell||a town, village, castle}}, borrowed from {{der|en|LL.|castellum||small camp, fort}}, diminutive of {{der|en|la|castrum||camp, fort, citadel, stronghold}}, possibly from {{der|en|ine-pro|*kat-||hut, shed}}. {{doublet|en|castell|castellum|château}}. Parallel borrowings (from Late Latin or Old French) are {{cog|sco|castel}}, {{m|sco|castell||castle}}, {{cog|fy|kastiel||castle}}, {{cog|nl|kasteel||castle}}, {{cog|de|Kastell||castle}}, {{cog|da|kastel||citadel}}, {{cog|sv|kastell||citadel}}, {{cog|is|kastali||castle}}, {{cog|cy|castell}}. The Middle English word was reinforced by {{der|en|xno|-}}/{{der|en|ONF.|castel}}, itself from Late Latin {{m|la|castellum||small camp, fort}} (compare modern French {{m|fr|château}} from Old French {{m|fro|chastel}}). If Latin {{m|la|castrum||camp, fort, citadel, stronghold}} is from Proto-Indo-European {{m|ine-pro|*kat-||hut, shed}}, {{cog|la|casa||cottage, hut}} is related. Possibly related also to {{cog|got|𐌷𐌴𐌸𐌾𐍉||chamber}}, {{cog|ang|heaþor||restraint, confinement, enclosure, prison}}. See also {{l|en|casino}}, {{l|en|cassock}}.

